commentBody:
@Sam 

Let's say you've never heard of either one because you're not an American.  Or for whatever reason.  They cross at the E.  Given that it is a [Gas relief brand], what letter could you conceivably infer to be the correct one?

Even Americans find crosses they know neither part of, but if the answer is inferable, intelligent citizens of everywhere can figure them out.  After all, it is a crossword.

@Marianne 

I’ve had a few puzzles published, and since I don’t often have good ideas for themes, I’ve tried to construct themeless puzzles. I’d be pretty proud if I could make one that’s three-fourths as good as this one. 

I believe that Mr Leach is not yet 21. Maybe his youth excuses a somewhat immodest constructor note?

@SP same here (but for different words…somehow GALEFORCE didn’t come easily for me but MANICPANIC did)

Glad this puzzle came out when it did as I had started to almost dread Saturday puzzles for how much they challenge me. Overall, I found this puzzle clever and refreshing, and I’m now headed to the archives to see if I’ve yet to tackle any of the creator’s other puzzles.

Happy Pride!

@Marshall Walthew 

I may be misremembering; the largest one may have been Lenin. 

I’d seen more traditional sets before then, but I hadn’t known what to call them.

@Adina
My only look-up was what is a Chordophone?  Not a word I knew.

This is why I don't consider look-ups cheating.  They are learning experiences!

@Darren B 

Standing Room Only;

all the seats are occupied

like a Broadway show

@Bill in Yokohama 

"Take that, all you substandard and inadequate solvers who didn't find this puzzle to be a snap."

Honestly, does anyone give any consideration at all how their comments may land on others anymore?

@Caitríona Shanahan "I was given a MATRYOSHKA with Gorbachev, Andropov, Brezhnev, Khrushchev, Stalin and a tiny Lenin years ago by a dear friend."

I was recently given one with Putin, Putin, Putin, Putin,  and a  tiny Putin inside. It matches another in my collection, also with a tiny Putin inside. 

(Have at, emus.)

@LBG 

I think you're misinterpreting the intent of posters who comment that a puzzle is too easy.  There are solvers of many different levels of experience here, and more skilled solvers would like to see a challenge in end of week puzzles.  That's how it used to be, and that's missed by many.  Imagine if every puzzle was at Monday level.  You might quickly tire of them if they started to feel like a fill-in-the-blank chore.

Since there are 3 guaranteed days of easy puzzles (and often 4 because Sunday usually falls in that range), it doesn't seem like too much to ask to have 3 more difficult puzzles, does it?  To me, it just seems fair.

@Nancy J.
See your point, but just don't think it applies here.  This was not, IMHO, a Sunday-through-Wednesday puzzle.  Merely an observation from one who's been doing these things since the days when the Shah was in power.

As ever, your wheelhouse may vary.

@LBG 

My point is only about assuming attitude on the part of other posters, not about the level of difficulty of this particular puzzle.

"Big day for the oh-so-hip I-finished-in-three-minutes crowd, eh?  Talk about you're so full of yourself...." just seemed a little judgy to me.

@Lewis 

CMON.  I know you made up "semordnilaps".

I'm not even going to google it, so sure am I that my leg is being pulled.

@Emma S 
What a lovely thing to say! You don’t know the half of it: I come from the Yorkshire Pennines where it snows from October to April (did before the climate collapsed). We would totter down the hill to town on black spiked heels, wearing not much more than a black bin liner and strategic safety pins, come snow, rain or both. The black eyeliner would smudge with the dripping hair colour on our way back,  Mohican hair spikes drooping,  thinking we looked the bees knees; yes, eating chips and scraps from a greasy paper bag to keep our hands warm.
The young of today? They don't know how to live. ;)

@Joe 

Leisure is a noun. Leisurely is an adjective. I don’t see what the problem is. I don’t see how you would use it as an adverb. 

Like timely. Homely.

@Barry Ancona

There's evidence the Moche were cultivating potatoes almost a 1000 years before the Inca.

<a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0305440318303327" target="_blank">https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0305440318303327</a>

@Roberto 

I think you just enunciated why KILO works here.  As a combining form, it works as an opening (kilogram, kilometer, kilobyte), meaning the same as grand, but working as an opening part of a word.

This clue is no different from clues like [Before opening?] for ANTE, [False start?] for PSEUDO or [Fresh start?] for NEO, all used within the past two years.

@JohnWM 
@Spencer L

I really need to get my eyes check.  Over and over I read the clue for 15D as "Relatively nice *person*, humorously.

Didn't realize my mistake until reading WordPlay.

So I just lucked into getting CLUBFED right.  It never made any sense to me, if I'm being honest.

@Linda Jo 

Yeah, I have *no* idea what they were thinking with that clue.

Your lampoon is perfect.

@Dan 

Happy Birthday Dan! 
I get it. This is my last year in my 70's. Next year I'll be in my 80's.  So far every year has been better than the last. So we puzzle along with the confidence that getting older remains so much nicer than the alternative. Cheers!

@Mike

Sounds like you're trying to ram this one down our throats then take it on the lamb.

Pun and run?

